ξ 123. The necessity of disinheriting a suus heres is grounded on the principle of primitive law, that the child is co-proprietor with the parent: hence, unless something occurs to divest the child of his property, he will simply become sole proprietor by survivorship on the death of his father. In suis heredibus evi- dentius apparet, continuationem dominii eo rem perducere, ut nulla videatur hereditas fuisse, quasi olim hi domini essent, qui etiam vivo patre quodammodo domini existimabantur. Unde etiam filius- familias appellatur, sicut paterfamilias, sola nota hac adjecta, per quam distinguitur genitor ab eo qui genitus sit.
